article.description: Ray Allen scored 28 points and hit two late off-balance shots to lift the Seattle Supersonics to a 90-81 win over the Philadelphia 76ers on Monday.
article.headline: Iverson calls it 'worst loss of the year'
article.linkText: Sonics' Allen proves better than Sixers in win
article.story:
PHILADLEPHIA -- Ray Allen made sure Seattle's rough road trip ended on a positive note. Allen scored 28 points and hit two late off-balance shots to lift the SuperSonics to a 90-81 win over the Philadelphia 76ers on Monday. Vladimir Radmanovic had 15 points, Rashard Lewis added 12 and Jerome James had 10 points and eight rebounds for the Sonics, who overcame a 19-point first-half deficit to end a four-game losing streak. Glenn Robinson scored 27 points for Philadelphia, which lost its third straight game. Allen Iverson was held to 18 points on 7-for-22 shooting. "This game right here wasn't played with any heart," Iverson told the Philadelphia Inquirer after the game. "We played well when things went right for us, but then, when things started to go bad, we couldn't even get it together." The win was the Sonics' lone highlight on a three-game road trip that included poor defense and several airport delays. "The road has been very unkind to us the first two games," Allen said. "It seems like, in every city, there was something wrong with one of our planes. On top of that, we were losing games. The cards were stacked against us." The Sonics opened the second half on a 13-0 run as the Sixers shot 0-for-11 and turned the ball over five times. Robinson ended the drought with a 10-foot jumper that started an 11-0 run. Seattle regained the lead early in the fourth with three straight 3s from Ronald Murray, Radmanovic and Allen. The Sixers stayed close, pulling within two with 3:07 to play before Allen hit an 18-foot fadeaway jumper and a 3-pointer while falling to the floor to put Seattle ahead by seven. Iverson and Robinson missed back-to-back 3s, and the Sonics hit four free throws around two from Iverson in the final minute to seal the win. "The first half, we looked a lot like ourselves the last few days," Sonics coach Nate McMillan said. "In the second half, we tightened up our defense and took care of the ball." Sixers coach Randy Ayers took longer than usual in speaking to the team and his assistants after the game. When Ayers took the podium for his postgame press conference, he appeared agitated. "I had a little bit more to say (in the locker room) tonight," Ayers said. "This is a really disappointing loss for us," Ayers told the Inquirer, "because as we get guys back from the injured list and back healthy, you are thinking you're back to full strength and have developed some depth, and we don't seem to understand how we have to play consistently with guys back." Iverson defended Ayers after the game, saying it is unfair to compare Ayers to Larry Brown, who resigned last year after six seasons with the team. "The guys that are not responding to (Ayers) don't need to play," Iverson said. "The guys that won't respond to him, that's up to guys like myself, Eric Snow and Aaron McKie to make sure they do." While Ayers was hesitant to characterize the loss as the worst of the season, Iverson was not as reserved. "Absolutely, it was the worst loss of the year by far," he told the Inquirer. "We played not to lose instead of playing to win. This really hurts." Seattle, which allowed Washington to shoot 51 percent in a loss Saturday, limited Iverson's drives in the lane and kept him off the foul line. Iverson attempted just six free throws, making four. "That was a big key, to keep him off the line," McMillan said. The Sixers started the game 8-for-10 and shot 62 percent in the first quarter to build a 12-point advantage. The lead reached 19 before Allen scored seven straight in a 12-4 run that brought the Sonics within 11. Lewis, who missed his six field-goal attempts in the first half, hit a pair of free throws to cut the halftime lead to 48-39. Kenny Thomas returned after missing two games with a right ankle sprain and had 14 points and 12 rebounds for the Sixers, who had a full 12-man roster for first time since Nov. 26. "I'm fine. It was like a miracle," Thomas said of his quick recovery.

Game notes
Before the game, the Sixers signed F Zendon Hamilton for the third time this season. Hamilton originally signed as a free agent on Dec. 10 before being waived on Jan. 6 and re-signed to a 10-day contract three days later. Hamilton did not play Monday. ... James picked up his third foul 3:52 into the game and sat the rest of the first half. ... The Sixers reached the halfway point of their schedule with 18 wins, three less than this point last season. ... Snow left the game with 47 seconds left with a bruised right leg. Information from The Associated Press and the Philadelphia Inquirer was used in this report.
